It is to show us as the public, the real and honest truth of REAL stories and real people about real topics; like corruption. Especially at the hands of what we as a society ingrain into our young people. Things I found interesting 
- The way he spoke about his stories. Laughing as if it wasn’t real or it was comedy. 
- The language he uses. You can live wherever you want in the world but using the term ‘cocksucker’ so flippantly & his lack of consideration when speaking on his ‘sexual favours’ speaks volumes about the culture in which he was brought up. 
- his sadness at the end - out of everything he spoke about, his parents are really what got him. How crazy is that? Out of all of the mistakes he’s made, his own family & children; it really came down to him mummy and daddy not providing him enough attention and wanting to be the alpha, with the power, the money, the life it gave him. 
Well done Stephen 👏👏👏👏

Raw and candid. Steve, you were solidly grounded during this interview. And asked poignant follow up questions.

Bad cops are real! Born and raised in Brooklyn. And the area where he was a cop, is one of the most difficult places to patrol. He made choices and certainly paid the consequences. And probably would not change it. And that’s his journey.
